---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import { getEntry } from 'astro:content'

const lainey = await getEntry('authors', 'lainey')
const avatarSrc = lainey!.data.avatar
---

<BaseLayout>
	<main class="app-container pt-36">
		<h1 class="text-6xl pb-2 font-bold">About</h1>
	</main>
	<section class="app-container py-12 mb-8">
		<div>
			<div
				class="relative prose prose-neutral prose-lg md:prose-xl dark:prose-invert prose-img:rounded-xl prose-figure:text-center prose-img:mx-auto"
			>
				<p>
					Research can be intense and often isolating. Much of what we write as postgrads is high stakes: thesis chapters, journal articles, funding proposals. These forms of writing matter, but they are tied to formal outcomes. It is easy to start writing only when something "counts", and to associate writing with pressure rather than with thinking. Higher education research distinguishes between high-stakes writing, which is formally assessed and consequential, and low-stakes writing, which supports learning and idea development without evaluation (<a href="https://www.bard.edu/wwwmedia/files/6790042/3/Elbow%20High%20Stakes%20and%20Low%20Stakes%20Assigning%20and%20Responding.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Elbow, 1997</a>).
				</p>
				<p>
					Research in higher education shows that writing is not only a way of reporting knowledge, but a way of developing it. A large meta-analysis found that regular writing activities are associated with improved academic performance across disciplines (<a href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.3102/00346543074001029" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Bangert-Drowns et al., 2004</a>). Studies of doctoral writing groups show that students learn not only from receiving feedback, but from reading and critiquing the work of others (<a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/03075070902785580" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Aitchison, 2009</a>). In peer-based writing environments, participants develop clearer arguments, stronger critical awareness, and greater confidence in their scholarly voice. Writing becomes a shared intellectual practice rather than a solitary task.
				</p>
				<p>
					Research on academic writing groups also shows that these spaces contribute to the development and reshaping of scholarly identity, helping researchers see themselves as active participants within a research community (<a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/0307507032000058109" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Lee and Boud, 2003</a>). This matters in a context where postgraduate researchers report significantly higher levels of anxiety and depression than the general population (<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/nbt.4089" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Evans et al., 2018</a>). A blog cannot change structural pressures within academia, but it can provide an additional space for connection, reflection, and intellectual exchange.
				</p>
				<p>
					This platform is a student-led, cross-discipline space for thoughtful but low-pressure writing. Posts may reflect on seminars, research progress, methods, conferences, or the everyday realities of post-grad. They are reviewed by a small student editorial team, not formally assessed. The site is managed collaboratively through GitHub, so contributors also gain experience with shared workflows and version control in a supportive setting. The aim is to encourage regular writing, constructive peer engagement, and visible intellectual life across AIMSIR, Decarb-AI, Co-centre for Climate+, the School of Maths, and anyone else interested.
				</p>
				<p>
					Research culture is built not only through formal publications, but through sustained conversation and shared practice. This blog is one small way of supporting that process.
				</p>
				<img
					src={avatarSrc}
					alt={lainey!.data.name}
					class="not-prose hidden md:block absolute bottom-0 h-24 w-auto object-contain"
					style="image-rendering: pixelated; right: -7rem;"
				/>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="flex justify-end md:hidden mt-6">
			<img
				src={avatarSrc}
				alt={lainey!.data.name}
				class="h-24 w-auto object-contain"
				style="image-rendering: pixelated;"
			/>
		</div>
	</section>
</BaseLayout>
